text: I love Guillermo Del Toro and much of the body of work he's done. He's very stylized and has a very distinct stamp that he leaves on all of his movies. Some have not been up to par, but for the most part they've all been wonderful. I did find this trailer a bit underwhelming. I've heard much buzz surrounding Crimson Peak and was interested to see the trailer, but I wasn't feeling it. I do think much of it has to do with Mia Wasikowska. I've never been a fan of her's and I tend to lean toward the feeling that she drags down any film that she's in. She usually plays the same character and she doesn't add much life to any scene she's in, and while I hate to base my opinion of her character off a 2 1/2 minute trailer, it does seem like her typical thing. I really wanted to like this trailer. I just didn't. I perked up when I saw Tom Hiddleston but I just couldn't get passed my complete indifference to Wasikowska. I'd rather love her or hate her, but I just don't even care about her which is bad to me. She's like the female Brecken Meyer. They could both disappear and I just wouldn't care. Might go see it when it comes out. Man I really wanted to love this trailer!

text: Is it just me, or do parts of the interior Crimson Peak mansion look like the Rose Red mansion from Stephen King's movie of the same name? ¬†Especially the closed in staircase at 0:15 and the long hallway at 0:17 (though the wall decor has some spikes added here) His name is even quoted in one of the comments for 'this' movie. ¬†I wonder if they used parts of that same house? ¬†I know the Rose Red house was an old manor that had been turned into separate apartments and then used for the mini-series, while parts of the Rose Red house were set pieces. ¬†I'd be very curious to know where Crimson Peak was filmed. ¬†  In any case, this looks like an actually well done horror movie. ¬†I've never been a fan of torture-porn horror, I'd much rather see a creepy good old fashion ghost/monster story, if it's well written of course. ¬†With Guillermo Del Toro behind it, I feel like this might actually be enjoyable. ¬†Would be nice to have a decent horror movie to see this upcoming Halloween season.

text: Spoiler: The ghost with the long hair is actually trying to save the blond girl from the other ghosts and the brother sister killers. It's been watching over her since she was a child as you see at the end, it even warns her about Crimson Peak.
author: AlmostOn TimeHero

text: Oh, I unraveled the plot with enough viewings. The brother and sister are immortal or long lived. They kill people as a sacrifice of some type to keep their immortality. One of the previous victims, the ghost with the longer hair, died in the bathtub which you see at 1:58. The ghost with the long hair, is the mother of the blond girl, whom has been watching over her, protecting her, since she was a baby, which is why she says she has been seeing ghosts all her life. What ties the Blond woman and the ghost with the long hair together, is the baby picture the Blond woman finds at 1:45. The blond woman was there in the past as a baby from the long haired ghost; the male killer is a potential father of hers. Very good story, can't wait to see it.
author: AlmostOn TimeHero

text: So after more viewings, I figured out how the brother and sister are immortal. At 1:16 you see these large locked tubs in the room. At 1:18, you see the board of the tub push up, meaning there is something locked in there. At 2:01 you see the contents of this one tub, a dead body. But not just any dead body, the body looks to be digested, missing skin and bones, also notice the red goo it is in. Drowned bodies bloat and retain their skins. So the brother and sister kill or trap people then put them in the tubs for the house to eat or digest, giving the brother and sister long life or immortality. Very nice-ah.

text: Mia Wasikowska also starred in Alice in Wonderland She was younger then, maybe 16, 17 Immature and had crazy colourful mad imaginations Nice dream-like things; talking animals, food and drink that change your size, Johnny Depp in a top hat and orange wig These were all in her imagination... Now she's older Her imagination has matured Grown darker Now when she falls asleep she no longer sees the nice things She sees images of horror and pain and lost love In the form of ghosts And skinless things And Tom Hiddlestone... Her first love was for a fictional group of spectacular beings, which made her happy and calm Then she grew up and left all her magical loved ones behind Instead growing to love living things She has dived headfirst into real life and is realising how horrible it can be Still living in her head Her dreams are influenced by real life's horrors  Underland is a metaphor for childhood, happy dreams and happy love  Crimson Peak is adulthood, love and horrors of lost love  End!

text: Del Toro, I didn't want to, but I wound up loving most of your work. Now you've lost me. This trailer is mismarketed and so is this film. It is NOT a 'gothic romance' and it is NOT a 'horror' or a 'thriller'. It just dances back and forth between elements of the three as if you had written all three complete stories in mind and just wound up making aesthetics, NOT the house itself, a key player. You don't even introduce us to the grounds in an ominous enough way or pull out great performances, either. You talked about this being an empowering film for women and it is the opposite of that. There are no clear villains or victims and while that worked in a film like The Devil's Backbone and The Golden Army, it does not work here. We want Hiddleston to be an all-out monster or a hero, not rape-bully and the same is true for the rest of this powerful cast; you got Alice, Loki, and a Jaeger Pilot and used them to form the flimsiest love triangle since The . . . so that was YOU that did that in The Hobbit! The metaphor between butterflies and moths is not nearly as dark as you think, either. It actually seems silly in this setting. While I think this has a place in film like 'Sleepy Hollow' was a Tim Burton film strictly this could be seen as strictly a Del Toro style of film; but are bloodlust for land from our protagonists (that's right, industrialists were just that, not heroic and selfless in the majority of their cases Carnegie was a once in a lifetime guy) and constant undertones of incest that have been building in your films really what you want the world to associate with you? I would've written the ending to show at least a photograph of Edith's mother courting Thomas to hint at either immortality through keeping the house and the two are desperate for that reason as well as isolated, or to find out that Edith's mother is cousin to the Sharpe family and that gives her a bloodlink that allows her to remove that dishonor from the family name. And why wasn't the ghost of her father looking out for her as well? Do you not believe in male ghosts for their own sake, just women's? If Edith could just 'see ghosts' and was not simply intuitive the way an unexplained Stephen King child gets telepathy, then why was she not 'seeing dead people' much, much more unless she could pinpoint her father telling her to ignore them or something? You had an interesting idea, but like so many people in art galleries you only got in a few pieces and didn't take in the depth of the whole exhibit. I think what Stephen King really found scary about your film was its budget, not the story. It's The Fall of the House with The Seven Flowers in the Attic. If you read, you'll be able to see how many disappointing ripoffs were given such a superficial picture. Some people might find this amusing, but I don't think you're sure of the group of messages that will be taken from it and that's not what an artist's approach to expression is.

text: This is not a film for modern audiences accustomed to cheap horror gimmicks like Paranormal Activity, Annabelle, or Ouija. This is a throwback movie and love letter to classic gothic horror like the films of Mario Bava, Dario Argento, Hammer horror films, the old dark house subgenre, and classic gothic literature like Edgar Allan Poe plus many other inspirations. Like most of Del Toro's work, the true horror of the story is not supernatural, but people themselves. As a fan of the classics, this movie was amazing!

text: This is a great film, but it is not a horror movie. This is a Gothic romance that focuses on the opposing forces of the Victorian period, the Industrial Revolution and the desire to return to a quasi medieval period. This is a quintessential example of what the Romantic movement was all about: strong emotions, a desire to live i a world full of mystery instead of scientific reason.  It's also a great ghost story.
